PROMPT 2 — JOB SCHEDULING
Prompt Text (FINAL – v1.2)
You are a construction project scheduler responsible for planning subcontractor tasks for a residential construction project in Melbourne. Based on the project timeline, subcontractor availability, and task dependencies, generate an optimized job schedule.
Project inputs:
Project start date: [date]
Project end date: [date]
Tasks list: [e.g., excavation, electrical, plumbing, framing]
Task durations (in days): [list]
Task dependencies: [e.g., plumbing after framing]
Subcontractor inputs:
Subcontractor name
Availability dates
Specialisation (task type)
Constraints:
Tasks must follow dependency order
Assign only qualified subcontractors
Avoid scheduling conflicts (no overlap for same subcontractor)
Minimise project delays and idle time
Output format:
Table with columns: Task | Assigned Subcontractor | Start Date | End Date | Status (Scheduled/Conflict)
Highlight any scheduling conflicts or delays
Provide a 2–3 line summary explaining schedule efficiency and risks
Do not assume missing data. Flag any incomplete inputs.
---
Workflow Task
Step 2 of subcontractor management workflow — triggered after subcontractor selection to allocate tasks and create a project schedule.
---
Problem Being Solved
Manual scheduling of subcontractors is complex and time-consuming, often resulting in task overlaps, delays, and inefficient resource utilisation. Poor scheduling leads to increased project costs and missed deadlines.
---
Automation Potential
Very High — AI can automate 80–90% of scheduling logic by organising tasks, assigning subcontractors, and identifying conflicts. Human oversight is required to validate feasibility and handle exceptions.
---
Risks & Limitations
Dependency errors: Incorrect task dependencies may lead to flawed schedules
Data gaps: Missing subcontractor availability can cause inaccurate assignments
Over-optimisation risk: AI may prioritise efficiency over practical site constraints
Mitigation:
Validate all task dependencies before execution
Require project manager review before finalising schedule
Allow manual overrides for real-world adjustments
